what is css?
css is cascading style sheet.

html provides structure,skeleton,description,semantics.
style sheet is a sheet in which add the value to the properties,like bg-color = red
color = pink
border = 1 px

what do u mean by cascading?
cascading means which property have to pick, means in <p> u tell the bg-color = yellow
then bg-color = purple
bg-color = brown
so, which property have to pick .

now the 4 factors on which we can decide which property have to pick or not.
==>Browser Support: Works across target browsers.
==>Flexibility: Adapts to responsive layouts.
==>Performance: Renders fast without lag.
==>Maintenance: Keeps code clean and scalable.

There are 3 types of css-inline css,internal css,external css.
==>inline css means adding teh styels within the tags.

//<!-- internal css
    <style>
        h1{
            background-color: brown;
        }
        h4{
            color:aquamarine
        }
        p{
            color: pink;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <!--inline css
    <h1 style="background-color: rgb(250, 300, 200)">CODING</h1>
    <h4>MUSKAN</h4>
    <p style="color:blue">Welcome dosto.</p>
</body>
, if this is there, there is a competition bw inline and internal css, so, inline css will win.and if u want internal css to win, so this is teh syntax:
h1{
            background-color: brown !important;
        }
==>only add "!important" to which property u want to apply.

now, external css, u have to follow 2 steps-first make css file like example.css and then, link it. by <link>.
**internal css are in head tag and external css linking part is also done in head tag.
, in external css, the new file that u add for styling, the syntax is like- h1{
                                  font-size: xx-large;

} 
that means the internal and external css, syntax is same.
is h1 applies the property and value to it, inlone css will win among inline,internal,external css;
now, if inline css styling is removed, then who will win, the stylong in order which applies it win.
==><link rel="stylesheet" href="lecture1.css">
    
    <!-- internal css
    <style>
        h1{
            background-color: brown !important;
        }
        h4{
            color:aquamarine
        }
        p{
            color: pink;
        }
    </style>, the exteranl win .
    if
     <!-- internal css
    <style>
        h1{
            background-color: brown !important;
        }
        h4{
            color:aquamarine
        }
        p{
            color: pink;
        }
    </style>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="lecture1.css">
    internal css will win.
    if u want specific styling then mark it important using "!important".

Now, what are selectors, as the name suggests selector means selected elements , and what to do  in selected elements apply styling to it. so, this is teh definition.
there are these 4 selectors used to apply styling to specifc elements- element,id,class,group.
1)<!--selectors
    <!--element selector
    <!--choose an element that u wnat to apply styling to it, i choose <p>-->
     <!--using internal css
     <style>p{
        background-color: brown;
     }
   </style>

